Consider the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

dyadic topology
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

: every rational of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $p/2^{n}$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

 odd and integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n>0$
\end_inset 

 is taken to be an open set.
 All points in between such dyadic rationals are taken to form an open set.
\layout Standard

One way to visualize this topology is as a binary tree.
 At the root of the tree is the point 1/2.
 At the next level, there is 1/4 and 3/4, and so on.
 Every such node in the tree is then taken to be an open set.
 At the leafs of the tree lie the irrationals, and the rationals not of
 the form 
\begin_inset Formula $p/2^{n}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

The topology differs from that of the canonical Cantor set: in that case,
 the intermediate nodes are not even considered to be a part of the topology.
 The leaf nodes are taken to be closed sets, which is how the Cantor set
 becomes a perfect set.
\layout Standard

The point of introducing this binary tree topology is ....
 Task: construct measures on this topology.
\layout Standard

Several remarks are in order.
 First, in the canonical Cantor set, each leaf was assigned a measure of
 zero.
 It should be clear that this choice is arbitrary, and that any measure
 can be assigned to the endpoints.
 The cardinality of the endpoints of the binary tree is the cardinality
 of the continuum, as can be seen by using more or less the same arguments
 used to discuss the cardinality of the Cantor set.
 Because of this, it is not unreasonable to believe that one may be able
 to construct measures that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

make sense
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 in the context of the real number line.
 In particular, such measures can make well-defined integrals and the like.
\layout Standard

Of interest are measures that are functions of, and possibly holomorphic
 functions, of the dyadic expansion.
 That is, consider the series 
\begin_inset Formula $\{ b_{k}:b_{k}\in\{0,1\},\, k\in\mathbb{N}\}$
\end_inset 

of binary digits given by the dyadic expansion of a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
x=\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{b_{k}}{2^{k}}\label{eq: binary expansion}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 This expansion is not unique, because for every dyadic number, there are
 two inequivalent expansions.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2=0.1000..=0.0111...$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, we conclude that the dyadic topology is finer than the the usual
 topology on the real numbers.
 In particular, the dyadic topology distinguishes all three of these cases:
 1/2 is a not in the middle of the tree (the root as it happens here), whereas
 the two inequivalent expansions belong to two different leafs at the end
 of the binary tree.
\layout Standard

Because this topology is finer than the usual topology on the real number
 line, one can define functions on this topology that would be ill-defined
 when considered on the real number line: in particular, the three points
 above map to just one point on the real numbers.
 However, it should be painfully clear at this point that this topology
 is compatible with the discussion the structure of dyadic fractals.
 It should also be clear that this topology is compatible with discussions
 of the closure of the upper half-plane when considering the limiting behavior
 of modular forms, Fuchsian groups, and ergodic processes.
\layout Standard

As an example, consider the Takagi curve.
 When considered on the real-number line, it has a derivative that seems
