\layout Subsubsection

Physical interpretation
\layout Standard

A physical interpretation can be given to the appearance of the question
 mark function.
 In the limit of large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset 

, any lattice configurations with long runs of repeated spins will have
 a very large energy (when 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset 

 is taken positive), and thus the exponential give such cases an exponentially
 small probability.
 In the dyadic mapping, long runs of repeated spins correspond to dyadic
 rationals: that is, numbers whose first few bits may vary, but whose binary
 expansion eventually terminates.
 Thus, for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset 

 has the binary expansion 
\begin_inset Formula $0.10000\ldots$
\end_inset 

 and the long string of zeros leads to a large energy and a small probability;
 in the limit of large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset 

 this becomes an infinite energy and a zero probability.
 This effect can be clearly seen in the graphs.
 Of course, strings such as 
\begin_inset Formula $0.100\ldots001$
\end_inset 

 are also disfavoured; in the dyadic mapping, such strings are located 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

near
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset 

, and account for the pronounced dip in that area.
 Similarly, strings near zero and one begin with (rather than end with)
 long runs of zeros and ones, and are also seen to be dis-favoured.
 (There is a possibility in principle, which does not occur here, of Anderson
 localized states, which are states having only a finite extent but still
 having finite energy.
 Viewed a s a subshift of finite type, localized states would be identified
 with instantons.
 The point is that the binary expansion for 1/2 need not have an 
\emph on 
a priori
\emph default 
 probability of zero.)
\layout Standard

Now, the question mark function maps the rational numbers to the dyadic
 rationals; in the Kac model, the dyadic rationals have a zero thermodynamic
 probability.
 In this sense, we may understand why the derivative of the question mark
 function is necessarily zero at all rationals.
 Conversly, one may see that the derivative of the question mark function
 is necessarily non-zero in those places where the strings of letter alternate,
 ad infinitum.
 A special case of alternating strings are periodic strings: strings that
 may begin with some random pattern, but eventually settle down to a periodic
 pattern.
 Periodic strings are interesting because thier energy can be precisely
 computed even in the limit of large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset 

.
 Periodic binary strings correspond to those rationals that are not dyadic;
 for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $2/3=0.10101\ldots$
\end_inset 

 These are the only such periodic strings, as there are no irrationals that
 have a periodic binary expansion.
 For the question mark function, periodic strings also have a significance:
 they correspond to the quadratic irrationals.
 This result was noted hundreds of years ago (by Gauss??), in the study
 of Diophantine equations: the solutions to the Diophantine equations are
 the quadratic irrationals, which may be specified as continued fractions
 with a periodic component in the continued fraction.
 The question mark function maps such periodic continued fractions to periodic
 binary strings: thus the quadratic irrationals and the rational numbers
 are in perfect one-to-one correspondance.
 
\layout Subsubsection

Gibbbs states and fractal self-similarity
\layout Standard

The physics of the Kac model provides insight to why the question mark has
 flat spots at every rational, and why its derivative is non-vanishing on
 the irrationals: only the irrationals are mapped to strings that don't
 terminate.
 In physics, such states are called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

Gibbs states
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

: they are the states that are associated with a finite thermodynamic energy.
 From the above presentation, we can deduce that the Gibbs states are in
 some sense 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

dense
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 in the space of all configurations; conversely, so are the non-Gibbs states.
 A rigorous notion of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

dense
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

, however, requires a topology; a topology for the lattice models is constructed
 in a later section.
\layout Standard

The Gibbs states may also be used to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

explain
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 the fractal self-similarity of the question mark function.
 Both the Ising and the Kac potentials are translationally invariant, in
 that the total energy does not change as the shift operator is applied
 to the lattice.
 The translation invariance is an explicit part of the construction: it
 is used in equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Classical Hamiltonian}

\end_inset 

 to construct the total energy.
 In a certain sense, the Gibbs states are precisely those states that are
 translationally invariant.
 That is, if one chooses some Gibbs state, and then chops off the leading
 binary digit, one must necessarily have another Gibbs state.
 
\layout Standard

At first blush, the matching of real numbers to lattice model configurations
 given by the dyadic map of equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dyadic map}

\end_inset 

 may seem arbitrary: one might imagine a large class of maps that could
 connect these spaces.
 The seeming fractal nature of the problem may be a trick of the mind, wrapped
 up in the mapping of equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dyadic map}

\end_inset 

 instead of being intrinsic to the physics of the configuration space.
 This concern raises two important questions: does there exist a non-fractal
 mapping from the space of configuration states to the real number line,
 and how should the concept of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

fractal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 be expressed on spaces, such as the space of states, whose topology is
 not naturally that of the real number line?
\layout Standard

A reasonable requirement on a map from the configuration space to the reals
 would be that it somehow preserves the translation invariance.
 Translation invariance is an important physical requirment for a lattice
 model, and one would like to have this requirement reflected in the mapping.
 That is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\Omega\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset 

 is some map that assigns a real number to each point 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\Omega$
\end_inset 

, the set of all possible states, then one might require that there exists
 a non-trivial function 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset 

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
(f\circ\tau)(\sigma)=(g\circ f)(\sigma)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

is the shift operator.
 This requriment that the mapping preserve translation invariance is simply
 a requriment that there exists a commuting diagram:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ccc}
\Omega & {f\atop \longrightarrow} & \mathbb{R}\\
\tau\downarrow &  & \downarrow g\\
\Omega & {\longrightarrow\atop f} & \mathbb{R}\end{array}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 It should now be clear that the representation of translation invariance
 on the real number line is a requirement that the mapping have a fixed
 point at which it is self-similar: that is, one must have 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
(f\circ\tau^{n})(\sigma)=(g^{n}\circ f)(\sigma)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 for all positive integers 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

.
 Translation invariance implies iteration; it is well understood that, in
 general, the iteration of functions of the real number line results in
 fractals.
 The above result is general; it applies to all one-dimensional lattice
 models, and is not dependent one the form of the interaction, or even on
 the number of states at a given lattice location.
\layout Standard

For the two-state model, there is another symmetry that one might expect
 to preserve: this is the symmetry under the interchange of the two states.
 In the absence of a magnetic-field-type interaction (so 
\begin_inset Formula $M=0$
\end_inset 

 in equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Ising potential}

\end_inset 

), one might expect an absolute symmetry.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho:\Omega\to\Omega$
\end_inset 

 be this reflection operator, the operator that, given a string of letters
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset 

, exchanges letter 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset 

 (or state -1) for the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset 

 (or state +1), and 
\emph on 
vice-versa
\emph default 
.
 Corresponding to this, one expects a function 
\begin_inset Formula $r:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset 

 that makes the following diagram commute: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ccc}
\Omega & {f\atop \longrightarrow} & \mathbb{R}\\
\rho\downarrow &  & \downarrow r\\
\Omega & {\longrightarrow\atop f} & \mathbb{R}\end{array}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Clearly, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{2}(\sigma)=\sigma$
\end_inset 

 the identity function, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{2}(x)=x$
\end_inset 

 is the identity as well.
 
\layout Standard

Given such a translation-invariant homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

, that has functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 acting as representations of tranlsation and reflection, one has in essence
 constructed everything that is needed to have a fractal with dyadic symmetry.
 That is, one need only to recognize that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 generate the dyadic monoid of the modular group 
\begin_inset Formula $SL(2,\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset 

.
 The elements of this monoid are of the form
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\gamma=g^{a}\circ r\circ g^{b}\circ r\circ g^{c}\circ\cdots\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c,\ldots$
\end_inset 

 are non-negative integers.
 
\layout Standard

This construction holds for essentially all two-state lattice models.
 That is, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

 be the translation-invariant homomorphism as above, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $h:\Omega\to X$
\end_inset 

 be just about any function to some space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset 

 which commutes with the reflection operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset 

