\layout Subsubsection

Measure theory and sigma-algebras on a lattice 
\layout Standard

From the above discussion, it is clear that taking the 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset 

 limit of a one-dimensional lattice model will require a way to promote
 the sums over configuration space into integrals.
 As pointed out in the introduction, this is not a trivial matter, because
 the cardinality 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{N}$
\end_inset 

 of the configuration space changes from finite to uncountable in the limit.
 In particular, it is known from measure theory that it is impossible to
 define integration on a point set with the cardinality of the continuum.
 To properly define integration, one must define a topology and a sigma-algebra
 first.
 A general presentation of this idea is given here.
\layout Standard

The machinery of measure theory forces a radical shift in the language,
 notation and concepts used to discuss the problem.
 First of all, one can no longer employ the idea that the space consists
 of a set of points.
 There is a reason for this: not every subset of of an uncountably-infinite
 set is "measurable".
 In fact, almost all subsets of an uncountably-infinite set are not measurable.
 So the very first step of measure theory is to throw away almost all subsets
 of the total space.
 One keeps only the measurable sets.
 The collection of measureable sets is countable, and to each such set one
 assigns a (non-negative) size or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

measure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

.
 This collection forms a topology, in the sense that the intersection or
 union of any two measureable sets is also a measureable set, and has a
 size.
 Such a collection of sets, equiped with a size, and obeying an additonal
 axiom, (that of sigma-additivity, to be defined), is called a sigma algebra.
 
\layout Standard

In this new language, the Hamiltonian takes on a new and very different
 appearance.
 It is no longer a function from points to the reals, but a function from
 elements of the sigma algebra to the reals.
 Intuitively, this "new" Hamilton can be visualized or intuited as the "average"
 of the old, classical Hamiltonian, the average taken over a certain subset
 of points.
 However, this intuition is dangerous, and can lead to errors: in particular,
 one has the chicken-and-egg problem of how to define the "average" of the
 old, classical Hamiltonian.
 The new Hamiltonian is different, and cannot be constructed from the old
 Hamiltonian.
 However, there is a way to prove that the new Hamiltonian is a faithful
 representation of the old one.
 If one has chosen one's sigma algebra wisely, then for every possible point
 in the old set, there is a sequence or filter or net of elements of the
 sigma algebra that contain the old point, and the measure of the elements
 in this sequence decreases to zero.
 
\layout Standard

Suppose that the elements of this net are denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset 

 for integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

, and have a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(a_{n})$
\end_inset 

 The net is ordered so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(a_{n})<\mu(a_{k})$
\end_inset 

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $n>k$
\end_inset 

.
 The "new" Hamiltonian is some function that assigns a real value to each
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset 

.
 We can then say that the new and the old Hamiltonians are equal or equivalent
 when, for the "classical" point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

, the following are satisfied: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
p\in a_{n}\quad\forall n\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}\]

\end_inset 

and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lim_{n\to\infty}\mu(a_{n})=0\]

\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{H(a_{n})}{\mu(a_{n})}=E_{p}\]

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{p}$
\end_inset 

 is the classical energy of the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

 which the net is converging to.
 Again: to be clear: the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

 is a possible configuration of the lattice model; each and every point
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

 corresponds to an infinite string in two letters, and vice-versa, in one-to-one
 correspondence.
 If a net can be found for all points 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

, and the above relationship holds for all points 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

, and it holds for all possible nets to the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

, then one may honestly and truthfully insists that the "new" and the "old"
 Hamiltonians "are the same".
\layout Standard

More generally, this sort of a measure-theoretic refomulation of integration
 over an uncountable set of points is refered to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

second quantization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 in physics, and the integration is refered to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

functional integration
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

.
 A word of caution: standard treatments of second quantization in physics
