\end_inset 

old
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 Hamiltonian shall be called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

classsical Hamiltonian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

, as it deals with points.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

new
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 Hamiltonian will be called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

quantum Hamiltonian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

, because the sigma algebra may be used to define functional integrals.
\layout Subsubsection

The cylinder set topology
\layout Standard

The natural topology for the configuration space of one-dimensional lattice
 models has a subbase that consists of cylinder sets.
 It is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

natural
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 in the sense that there is a simple and natural action of the shift operator
 on the cylinder sets, and that there is a natural way to assign a size
 to the cylinder sets.
\layout Standard

The subbase of a topology is a collection of sets such that any finite intersect
ion or union of such sets belongs to the topology, and that furthermore,
 every set in the topology can be written as a finite intersection or union
 of sets in the subbase.
 
\layout Standard

A sigma algebra then consists of the topology, together with a function,
 the measure, that assigns a non-negative, real value to every element of
 the topology.
 The measure must satisfy a property called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

sigma-additivity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

: the measure of the union of a number of disjoint sets must equal the sum
 of the measures of each set.
 Notationally, sigma-additivity requires that:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mu\left(\bigcup_{i\in I}\, a_{i}\right)=\sum_{i\in I}\mu\left(a_{i}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where each of the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset 

 are pairwise-disjoint from the other sets, and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset 

 is a (countable) collection of indecies of the sets being considered.
\layout Standard

The cylinder sets may be defined as follows.
 Let the positions on the lattice be labelled by an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

.
 The elements of the subbase of the sigma algebra can be completely enumerated
 by ordered pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(n,s)$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

 is a string in two letters of finite length 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

, for integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k<\infty$
\end_inset 

.
 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(n,s)$
\end_inset 

 is to be visualized as the set of all states where the lattice values between
 location 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n+k-1$
\end_inset 

 are equal to the string 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{(n,s)}$
\end_inset 

 denote an element of this subbase.
\layout Standard

The subbase of a topology is a collection of sets, which, by intersection
 and union, generate the rest of the topology.
 A brief review of intersection and union is in order.
 The intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{(n,s)}\cap C_{(m,t)}$
\end_inset 

